        "text": " search engines (such as Netflix, LinkedIn, and Spotify). Rather than evaluating all 1 million jobs using a heavy, precise algorithm, the"
      }, {
        "text": " process is split into two phases:\n\n*   **Stage 1: Cheap Retrieval (High Recall, Low Cost):** \n    "
      }, {
        "text": "First, the system applies hard constraints (e.g., target job title, location, salary, experience level, and a"
      }, {
        "text": " few core required skills) using highly efficient inverted indexes (like Elasticsearch, OpenSearch, or ClickHouse). \n    *"
      }, {
        "text": "   This instantly narrows the pool of 1,000,000 active jobs down to a highly relevant subset"
      }, {
        "text": " of **1,000 to 5,000 candidate jobs** in less than 5 milliseconds.\n"
      }, {
        "text": "*   **Stage 2: Accurate Re-ranking (Low Recall, High Precision):**\n    Now, the exact"
      }, {
        "text": ", computationally heavy \"skill-matching\" algorithm is executed *only* on those 1,000 to 5,000"
      }, {
        "text": " candidate jobs. Evaluating a user\u0027s 100 skills against 1,000 jobs requires only 10"
      }, {
        "text": "0,000 comparison operations—which modern CPU architectures can process in **2 to 5 milliseconds**.\n\n---"
      }, {
        "text": "\n\n### 2. Replacing Vector Embeddings with Skill Ontologies (Knowledge Graphs)\nWhile dense vector embeddings (like cosine"
      }, {
        "text": " similarity) are great for fuzzy, conceptual matching, they are computationally heavy, suffer from \"loss of detail,\" and can make"
      }, {
        "text": " mistakes (for example, treating \"Java\" and \"JavaScript\" as highly similar because they share letters and domains). \n\nTo"
