1,000,000 \\text{ jobs} \\times 15 \\text{ skills/job}}{5,000 \\text{ global skills}} \u003d 3,000 \\text{ jobs}$$\n\nFor **one single user** with 100 skills, the maximum number of arithmetic operations (Multiply-Accumulate, or MACs) required to find all overlapping job scores is:\n$$100 \\text{ user skills} \\times 3,000 \\text{ jobs/skill} \u003d 300,000 \\text{ operations}$$\n\nFor **all 100,000 users** against **all 1,000,000 jobs**, the total number of operations is:\n$$100,000 \\text{ users} \\times 300,000 \\text{ ops/user} \u003d 30,000,000,000 \\text{ (30 Billion) MACs}$$\nEach Multiply-Accumulate operation consists of 1 multiplication and 1 addition, totaling **60 Billion Floating-Point Operations (FLOPs)**.\n\n---\n\n#### 2. Actual Runtime Estimates\n\n##### **On a Single User Query (Real-time Web Request)**\n*   **Raw computation time:** A single modern CPU core can easily compute 300,000 sparse operations in **less than 0.2 milliseconds**. \n*   If we use **Block-Max WAND**, we skip ~90% of the computations, reducing the active evaluation to ~30,000 operations, which takes **under 0.05 milliseconds**.\n*   *Verdict:* In a real-time web application, the calculation itself takes virtually zero time; the only latency is the network I/O and database retrieval (usually **5 to 15 milliseconds** total).\n\n##### **On the Entire 100K Users × 1M Jobs Batch (Offline Ranking)**\nSparse matrix-matrix multiplication (SpGEMM) is bound by memory bandwidth, not CPU clock speeds. \n\n*   **On a Modern Multi-Core CPU Server (e.g., 64-core AMD EPYC using Threading \u0026 Intel MKL):**\n    A 64-core server can achieve a sparse compute throughput of roughly 30 to 50 GFLOPs/second.\n    $$\\text{Runtime} \\approx \\frac{60 \\text{ Billion FLOPs}}{40 \\text{ GFLOPs/sec}} \\approx \\mathbf{1.5 \\text{ to 3 seconds}}$$\n\n*   **On a Enterprise GPU (e.g., NVIDIA A100 or H100 using cuSPARSE/PyTorch):**\n    GPUs are massively parallel and highly optimized for sparse matrix calculations. An NVIDIA A100 can process 60 Billion sparse FLOPs in **less than 100 milliseconds**. \n    *   *Note:* Sorting the top-100 matched jobs for all 100,000 users (using a parallel GPU Radix Sort) will add about 50 milliseconds of overhead.\n    *   $$\\text{Total GPU Runtime} \\approx \\mathbf{150 \\text{ milliseconds}}$$\n\n### Summary\nBy transforming the hierarchical weights into a pre-weighted flat sparse vector, you convert a complex routing problem into basic matrix math. If implemented correctly using **SpGEMM on a single GPU**, you can calculate and rank the best matches for all 100,000 users against all 1,000,000 jobs in **less than a quarter of a second**.",
